<DOC><DOCNO> AP880607-0108 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1243EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Mother-Teresa-Cloth     06-07 0170</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Mother-Teresa-Cloth,0174</SECOND><HEAD>Inmates Counting Their Blessings After Mother Teresa's Visit</HEAD><DATELINE>CONCORD, Mass (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two state prison inmates hope to profit fromMother Teresa's recent visit by cutting up a seat cloth the Catholicnun used and selling the 50 pieces for $1,000 a square.   Ralph Woodward, who is serving 11 to 20 years for breaking andentering, said he and another inmate claimed a cloth that covered aplace where Mother Teresa sat during a special Mass at the Concordprison Saturday.   Woodward said they will use the money for such things aseducation after they leave prison.   ``We just feel that this is a blessing bestowed upon us,''Woodward told The Boston Globe. ``The fact that she came here is amiracle and now we have the cloth _ well, it's just phenomenal. Andthe fact that other people will have the pieces will just spread theblessing around.''   Mother Teresa, who founded a charitable order in India, visitedthree Massachusetts prisons Saturday during a national tour.</TEXT></DOC>